## Page 1: Introduction & Scope

This document covers **essential free backend tools** that work well with websites and web apps built in React, focusing on services with generous free tiers rather than fully paid enterprise platforms.[1][2][3] The emphasis is on tools that let you move quickly: managed backends, hosting platforms, and data-layer helpers that handle authentication, databases, APIs, and serverless logic with minimal boilerplate.[1][4][2]

We are not trying to list every niche product, just a practical short list you can rely on for most early-stage React projects.[1][2][3] Where tools overlap, we’ll call out how they differ so you can pick the one that matches your project constraints (self-host vs hosted, SQL vs NoSQL, real-time vs simple CRUD, etc.).[4][2] All tools mentioned here either have a usable free tier or can be self-hosted for free on commodity infrastructure, though some may charge as you scale.[1][5][3]

***

## Page 2: Backend-as-a-Service (BaaS) Overview

Backend-as-a-Service (BaaS) platforms give you a hosted database, authentication, APIs, and sometimes file storage and real-time features, exposed via SDKs that work cleanly with React.[1][4][2] For solo devs or small teams, this is usually the fastest route to a production-ready backend because the provider handles infrastructure, backups, and much of the security configuration.[1][4]

Typical components you get out of the box include a managed SQL or NoSQL database, REST or GraphQL APIs, user accounts with OAuth providers, role-based or row-level access control, and storage buckets for files.[1][4][2] React apps consume these via official JavaScript SDKs and often dedicated React hooks, which reduces boilerplate and improves type safety in TypeScript projects.[4][2] The trade‑off is vendor lock-in and pricing that ramps up once you pass free-tier limits, which is why choosing a platform with good portability can matter long term.[4][2][3]

***

## Page 3: Supabase – SQL-first Open Source Backend

Supabase is an open-source backend-as-a-service built on PostgreSQL that provides a hosted database, authentication, storage and real-time subscriptions with a generous free tier.[1][4][2] It auto-generates REST APIs for your schema, offers row-level security at the database layer, and includes a dashboard with a SQL editor and table viewer, which makes it easy to inspect and tweak your data model during development.[1][4]

For React developers, Supabase ships a JavaScript SDK (`@supabase/supabase-js`) and React-oriented tooling, including TypeScript types and hooks that integrate well with frameworks like Next.js.[1][2] This lets you implement auth flows, database queries and real‑time subscriptions using idiomatic React patterns without managing your own Node.js API layer for common CRUD cases.[1][4][2] Because Supabase is built on standard Postgres and is open source, you also have the option to migrate to self-hosted Postgres or another platform later without rewriting your entire data model.[1][4]

***

## Page 4: Firebase – Mature Managed Backend Platform

Firebase is a long‑standing BaaS from Google that offers managed databases (Cloud Firestore and Realtime Database), authentication, file storage, cloud functions, and messaging on a free tier suitable for small projects.[1][3] It has strong ecosystem integrations, extensive documentation, and a dashboard that brings all its services—database, auth, storage, analytics—into one place.[1][3]

In React apps, you integrate via the Firebase JavaScript SDK, wiring your components to Firestore or Realtime Database for data and using auth modules for email/password or OAuth sign‑in.[1][3] Firestore’s document-based model fits many typical web app use cases, but it requires different thinking from relational SQL, especially around querying and data structure design.[1][3] Firebase is attractive if you want minimal backend management and are comfortable with Google Cloud lock‑in and a NoSQL data model.[1][3]

***

## Page 5: Convex – Reactive Real-time Backend for React

Convex is a modern backend platform that keeps frontend state automatically in sync with backend data using a TypeScript-first, reactive programming model.[2] It provides real‑time data synchronization so React components stay updated without you hand‑rolling websockets or polling logic.[2]

Convex offers “best-in-class” React hooks and a full TypeScript end‑to‑end experience, which is useful for collaborative apps where many users are editing or viewing shared data in real time.[2] The platform handles reactive updates and real-time events for you, so you focus on writing TypeScript functions that define your backend behavior.[2] The main caveats are that Convex is relatively new, proprietary, and has its own mental model for data and reactivity, so there is a learning curve and less flexibility than running your own database.[2]

***

## Page 6: Appwrite – Self-hosted Open Source Backend

Appwrite is an open-source, self-hostable backend platform that exposes authentication, databases, storage, and functions via a REST API and SDKs.[5] It is designed to give you many of the conveniences of BaaS while letting you run the stack on your own infrastructure if you don’t want to depend on a single cloud vendor.[5]

For React apps, Appwrite provides a JavaScript SDK you can call from the browser or from a Node.js backend, handling login, database operations, and file uploads.[5] Because it is self‑hostable, you can pair Appwrite with low‑cost VPS or container hosting, effectively creating a free or very cheap backend environment once you absorb the operational overhead.[5] This suits teams that value control and on‑prem options over fully managed services.[5]

***

## Page 7: Free Hosting & Serverless Options (Vercel, Railway, etc.)

Beyond dedicated BaaS products, you can host your own backend code for free using platforms that provide serverless functions or containerized app hosting.[5][6] Vercel’s free tier, for example, lets you deploy serverless functions alongside your React frontend, which is ideal for small APIs, webhooks, and auth glue code.[5]

Railway, Fly.io, and similar platforms offer free tiers to run backend services or containers, which can host Express, NestJS, or any custom Node.js/TypeScript backend.[6][5] These services are useful when you outgrow simple BaaS patterns and need bespoke backend logic, but still want to avoid managing full servers.[5] The trade‑off is that free tiers have resource and usage limits, so you need to keep an eye on cold starts, CPU/memory caps, and project quotas.[6][5]

***

## Page 8: ORMs and Data Layer Tools (Prisma)

Prisma is an open-source ORM for Node.js and TypeScript that provides a type-safe query builder, a migration system, and a GUI (Prisma Studio) for visualizing and editing your database.[4][7] You define your schema in Prisma’s DSL and it generates a strongly typed client, which catches many data-layer errors at compile time in a React + TypeScript workflow.[4][7]

Prisma is not a backend‑as‑a‑service; it sits in your own backend code (for example, a Node.js API deployed to Railway or Vercel) and talks to databases like PostgreSQL, MySQL, and MongoDB.[4] You can even use Prisma with Supabase’s Postgres database, combining Supabase’s managed hosting and auth with Prisma’s type-safe queries and migrations.[4][7] This is useful when you want more complex business logic and schema control than a pure BaaS approach usually encourages.[4]

***

## Page 9: Recommended Stacks by Use Case

For a fast MVP with a React frontend and a relational database, Supabase plus React (or Next.js) is a strong choice: Postgres, auth, storage, and real‑time in one package, with a free tier.[1][4][2] If you prefer NoSQL and tight integration with Google’s ecosystem (including analytics and messaging), Firebase plus React and Cloud Functions can get you to production quickly.[1][3]

For highly collaborative, real‑time apps where automatic client syncing matters more than raw flexibility, Convex plus React gives you reactive hooks and zero‑config real‑time out of the box.[2] If you want full control and the ability to self-host, Appwrite plus a React frontend and perhaps Prisma or another ORM on top of a database gives you an open-source stack you can run anywhere.[5][4] When you need custom backend logic with minimal cost, pairing Prisma with a Postgres instance on a free tier host like Railway or Fly.io and deploying your React frontend on Vercel is a pragmatic route.[6][5][4]

***

## Page 10: Finishing Page

In practice, most React teams will be well served by starting with a BaaS (Supabase or Firebase) and only moving to self‑hosted or heavily customized stacks once their domain logic and scale justify the complexity.[1][4][3] Supabase stands out for SQL‑first, open-source flexibility; Firebase for maturity and integrations; Convex for real‑time React ergonomics; Appwrite for self‑hosted control; and Prisma for type‑safe data access in custom backends.[1][4][2][3][7]

You can treat this document as a starting map: pick the stack that most closely matches your current constraints—data model, hosting preferences, team experience—and evolve from there as the project grows.[1][4][2][3] Future library documents can dive deeper into hands‑on setup guides, code examples, and migration patterns between these tools for React applications.[1][4][2]

